{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012CYq92qmU1ipmCwBnPnH2e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**Root cause:** The `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only had a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`) with no RabbitMQ targets.\n\n**Fix applied (two changes to the ConfigMap, no new resource types):**\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** targeting all 3 pods by their stable headless-service DNS names (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`) with `metrics_path: /metrics`.\n\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rabbitmq_rules.yml` key in the same ConfigMap, referenced via `rule_files`) that maps `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` → `rabbitmq_up`. The built-in RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't expose a `rabbitmq_up` metric itself — Prometheus generates `up` per-target, so the recording rule bridges them.\n\n**Final state:**\n- 3 RabbitMQ targets: all `state=up`, no errors\n- `rabbitmq_up` query: 3 samples, all value=1\n- RabbitMQ pods: all 3 `Running`, 0 restarts"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":446,"cache_read_input_tokens":38447,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":446},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c9889f3c-a4e8-4185-8fe4-a9aef2e58f86","uuid":"ec477d2e-de7e-42ec-90e4-107090b513b2","request_id":"req_011CcdEGGvEj7iZNVgVrexiY"}
